text:
#youknowher 
she's the girl who smiles at you when you catch eyes - she doesn't speak, but the eyes say it all. she's the girl who would give you the shirt off her back, when underneath there's not much left to spare. she's the girl who laughs with you at jokes that may not be funny, but laughing beats crying. you might find her dancing in the rain, giving long hugs, and even striving for change. but, did you know...this girl doesn't find love for herself? and did you know, it's solely because of the world around her - her ego. 
now, this isn't a sad post- this post is about the reality of the life we all live. 
celebrities are taking their lives because they can't handle the pressure of perfection. our president doesn't care about our mental health and the damage he has done to those who have already fought so hard for their rights. we no longer walk into schools without a little fear inside of us, or attend concerts without wondering if we should be wearing bullet proof vests. 
when does it end? when does this idea of "influencers" and "top models" fade out, so that the young girls and boys who are still finding themselves, don't fall into the same awful circle of life we did. perfection is overrated, and under-defined. 
we are all perfect when at full potential.. we are all exactly who and what and where we need to be, as long as we are present. be thankful we walk amongst others who have lived entirely different lives, those are the ones who will teach us- they are the reason we will grow. 
this girl right here - has fought battle after battle, darkness upon darkness, and here she stands. i may not be screaming #metoo ,or telling my full story of neglect and mistreatment, to the world, but i'm here to look in the mirror and start a chain reaction of change... as my boy, mike j, once said, "if you want to make the world a better place take a look at yourself and then, make a change." here's to monday rolling in smooth. a fresh breath of air. 
a restart 
a "movement moment" 
whatever you need to do for yourself to help change the world - i challenge you to do that.

text:
sorry for the second post.  this is my #metoo story. wish that there was not an occasion for me to post it, however i think that is has arisen today.
know that my story is not significant. it is a bratty, whining complaint compared to the traumatic incidents experienced by people across the world. (note: it is not legitimate for me to say that i was â€œsexually harassedâ€ because it is uncertain whether the experience can be legally classified as sexual harassment.  the interactions that i had with and advances that i received from the coworker, however, were certainly uncomfortable for me.)â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”â€”last month, i became acquainted with a photographer who was looking for models for his personal photography project, and i volunteered to appear [clothed] in his photographs. it was exciting to be part of a project and work with an photographer and be a collaborator in a creative endeavor.  when i volunteered for this project, did not know that i would be asked to send nude photographs [that were unrelated to the project]. it seemed like he was making dirty jokes at first, therefore i declined politely and tried to continue investing work in the project. he did continue to make inappropriate comments and request nudes, and i continued to decline, becoming more adamant that he stop asking for it. over time, was sending him a lot of messages trying to tell him that i was uncomfortable with his comments/requests. could never get an answer from him because he would ignore me, therefore sent him messages repeatedly in an effort to address the issue. he hated the amount of messages, told me i was being pushy, and cancelled the project.  feeling guilty for annoying him, i apologize and asked how i could improve as a client and a friend (since i cared about the art project). continued in comment section.

text:
this is my contribution to the #metoo movement. i tried to capture the feelings that many women are having using symbolic imagery. defeat, oppression and struggle are represented by the vines and the fact that her back is turned toward the audience. the stained glass window is the church, which is often used as a weapon. the candles are the voices that have come before. i also wanted to show hope. the flowers are the movement - the women who are finally coming forward with their testimony. the butterfly is the metamorphosis and change that will hopefully come. #metoomovement #metoo #womenempowerment #women #expressiveart #newpainting #oilpainting #oiloncanvas #artbuyers #paintingforsale #artforsalebyartist #artforsale #paintingfromlife #emergingartist #art_we_inspire #artgram #seekinspirecreate #beautyfrompain

text:
everyday...some people just leave lasting imprints on our souls...some good...some horrifying...but they both mold who we are...these last few weeks have made two of the souls very heavy on my mind.  as i sit and see this next wave of grandkids i totally understand when my grandmother (who was the only mom i knew) said your heart grows each time a baby is born...there is no amount of grandkids that would change their love for me...my grandpa (my dad) reassured me numerous times...i was an anxious kid...i never thought about it until it got severe...i was so anxiety and guilt ridden (over being a girl and being alive...over being sexually abused...over not being protected...#metoo ) their love was the one thing i could always count on...they were home to me.  i miss them  so very much...here is a shout out to all those #grandparents who always go that extra step...gives that extra hug and one more just in case...i have fallen short as a nona in comparison  but i'm certainly trying and i hope i'm one of those souls to my grandkids.

text:
cw: sexual assault
day #365
it's difficult to believe that a year has passed. it has been a tumultuous time, full of heartbreak and sorrow, along with tremendous love and compassion. it's an uphill battle, but is slowly improving as i better utilize the tools to cope with trauma and severe depression. some days, i feel ready to take on the world, and others, i want to cry and hide away from the realities and horrors of the world we live in. 
the u.s. president admits to molesting women - not that big of a deal. a brazilian presidential candidate asserts  that he wouldn't rape a coworker because she wasn't "worthy" of it - still gets elected. but when a woman comes forward with her story of an attempt of assault against her, it must be fake because she didn't immediately report it, and because it comes at the risk of tarnishing the name of a man with a good career ahead of him, as if the years of living through her own trauma did not matter. 
any time someone says that, i want to ask them if they have been in her shoes before. do they actually know what it is like to go to the police? being repeatedly interrogating and reliving it, lying on the cold exam table during the rape kit, not being able to close that chapter of your life because a year later, the case is still ongoing? because if you don't know what it is like, i can tell you the details of why this past year after i was raped has by far been the most difficult in my life, and why a huge part of me wishes i hadn't reported it. 
studies show that only 2-8% of reported assaults are fake, which is the same rate as other felonies. so why do people rush to believe that the survivor is lying? i was often terrified to talk about what happened, because the doubt of one person was more powerful than the support of five people. i believe dr. ford, just as my friends have believed me. and if your initial impulse is to believe the assailant and not the survivor, then you are part of the reason why people don't come forward and you are part of the problem of misogyny in america.

#metoo #believesurvivors #ibelieveher #ibelievechristine  #notmypresident

text:
medusa would really like some company - pen and ink and acrylic on bristol - 11x14
there is a subliminal collective force working to be expressed in my art. i wasn't sure why i wanted to draw medusa, or why she might be offering cherry pie. only after she was complete did i understand what needed to be expressed. medusa was devoted priestess of athena's temple, known for her extraordinary beauty. the attention medusa received caused athena to be jealous. when medusa walked by the ocean the god poseidon desired her. as priestess to the temple she had to remain a virgin so she rejected poseidon. when he pressured her she ran to athena's temple for protection, but was not protected. 
poseidon raped her. 
poseidon wasn't punished. 
medusa was punished by athena. 
cursed with a mane of snakes to replace her glorious hair, any man who looked in her eyes would be turned to stone. 
she looks straight out from the page, a life of her own, born from my pen but independent of me. like the previous drawing of sister mary aquinas she has so much to say that still remains mysterious. i see she is lonely, but she has warmth. 
i would love to know if she speaks to you.
.
.
.
.

name: Lisa Winika
tweet_full:
medusa would really like some company - pen and ink and acrylic on bristol - 11x14
there is a subliminal collective force working to be expressed in my art. i wasn't sure why i wanted to draw medusa, or why she might be offering cherry pie. only after she was complete did i understand what needed to be expressed. medusa was devoted priestess of athena's temple, known for her extraordinary beauty. the attention medusa received caused athena to be jealous. when medusa walked by the ocean the god poseidon desired her. as priestess to the temple she had to remain a virgin so she rejected poseidon. when he pressured her she ran to athena's temple for protection, but was not protected. 
poseidon raped her. 
poseidon wasn't punished. 
medusa was punished by athena. 
cursed with a mane of snakes to replace her glorious hair, any man who looked in her eyes would be turned to stone. 
she looks straight out from the page, a life of her own, born from my pen but independent of me. like the previous drawing of sister mary aquinas she has so much to say that still remains mysterious. i see she is lonely, but she has warmth. 
i would love to know if she speaks to you.
.

text:
one of my least favourite words is should..
.
think about it. notice how often you use it, with yourself, others, in thoughts too.
i love that alexandra jamieson or @deliciousalex encourages people to "stop shoulding all over yourself."
.
i try very hard to follow her advice.
.
speaking of which, be mindful before dispensing advice. first of all, has it been solicited of you? no? then ask permission before offering it. second, check context before you so generously try to "help." if you're that dumbass who states the obvious, thoughtlessly...stfu. and don't get offended when people call you out for it. 
what? don't like being on the receiving end of advice?!! neither does anyone. stop acting like the freakin' advice fairy. ok?
.
i've seen an a**hole tell a bereaved mother at the funeral, that her son should have been wearing his helmet because that way he might've survived the accident. .
i've watched a domestic violence victim with her teeth knocked out, being told by her employer that she should have gone to the cops as soon as the drunk husband started hitting her.
.
i've had countless people with #metoo stories be told, "you should always report these things immediately. no point crying later."
.
so as you see, all these oh so generous advice givers may have imagined they meant well but i'd really like you to ask yourself, would you like hearing these things if you were that bereaved mother, the domestic violence victim, the #metoo survivor? so think first, advise later. .
oh yeah and this is another small lesson, for free, like all the gyaan that seems to be offered so magnanimously, advise is the verb, advice is the noun. get that right before you go around acting like you know better about everything. .
you're welcome ğŸ˜ğŸ˜‚ğŸ˜†ğŸ˜…ğŸ˜‰
.
#advice #unsolicitedadvice #whoaskedyou #shoulding #shouldingalloveryourself #alexandrajamieson

text:
this week has been the epitome of sunshine after rain. i crumpled into k last night after work and cried, relieved this week was over. i begrudgingly went to jury duty this week, which serendipitously allowed me the opportunity to be at the courthouse to sit by my sweet friend's side as her own case's verdict was being read. her assailant, whom she had to be in the same room with for three straight days, was found guilty of sexual assault iii and harassment. a year of pent up emotion came out after the word, "guilty" was spoken by the judge, and we both sobbed. she spoke her truth and the jury listened. her strength and poise was nothing short of astonishing, but this also reinstated in me the acknowledgment of why not all people report sexual assault. it's traumatic as hell to repeat to strangers, friends, and family over and over again, how you were attacked. and then, your integrity and reputation are attacked in order to prove you wrong. no wonder people are afraid to come forward. i wish i could say this more eloquently, but i'm so incredibly proud of my sweet friend, @adrienne.moscheo. thank you for giving us hope, courage, and for speaking your truth.

#metoo #speakyourtruth

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the start.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the bombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on my bed.

the whole qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is obvious that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing for the 2016 election.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are just helpless with the content and more or less fake accounts - there is no way they are going to risk their business by taking the responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole thing is build on the same user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
the poet carolyn forchÃ© describes poems of witness as bearing â€œthe trace of extremity within them . . . the poem might be our only evidence that an act has occurred.â€ traditionally, this has meant bearing witness to atrocities like war or genocide, but we will take a more expansive look at the form and how to bear witness to our own lives and to our own stories. this could include bearing witness to homophobia or racism, environmental degradation, or sexual harassment (#metoo), but it could also include bearing witness to difficult relationships, to a health crisis, or to the death of someone we love. in this workshop, we will read and discuss poems of witness, generate our own poems of witness through writing prompts, and workshop our writing together.
.
.
.
poetry of witness. poetry as trace with andrea scarpino is friday, november 16, 2018, 5:30 to 8:30 p.m. bear witness to our witness at http://piper.asu.edu/classes. .
.
.

text:
- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text: friday was truly one for the books. to be surrounded by so many incredible speakers and people who are fighting hard for equality, love and rights. it is so important that we get out and vote on november 6th! vote for our future, for our education, for womenâ€™s rights to their own body, for our children, for our earth, for our neighbors/peers, for elizabeth cady stantonâ€™s fight and all the leaders that came before and after. we canâ€™t just be the change we wish to see, we must also vote for the change we wish to see. read the sample ballots, understand who and what youâ€™re voting for. get involved and care. our county is suffering hard, with too much division and hatred and not enough morality, humanity or love. we are stronger together. so if you are voting by mail, make sure to get your ballots in before or by this coming tuesday, october 30th! for poll voters, go to your local county elections website to see what times you can go vote on nov. 6, early voting is available too!! vote local, state, federally! please. please. our voices will be heard!! #vote #mybodymychoice #humanrights #marchforourlives2018 #metoo #animalrights #climatechangeisreal #lovenothate #makeamericakindagain #blacklivesmatter #womensrightsarehumanrights #lovewins

text:
âœ§complex ptsd criteria: part 4 âœ§
today's criterion is a pretty difficult subject. tough, but very important. it involves "distorted perceptions of one's perpetrator".
.
survivors of prolonged trauma must do any and all they can to just survive. for many with c-ptsd, they were only children at the time and fully dependent on their perpetrator(s). believing these individuals were bad guys would force awareness that even their most basic needs were in jeopardy. adults facing domestic violence are also often wholly dependent on the person causing them harm - typically because the abuser sets it up that way. this can cause the mind to cling to rather distorted beliefs about them just to hold on.
.
for some, a belief system that nearly idolizes the perpetrator takes root. they may see them as incapable of doing harm; everything they do is out of love and care, even that which causes pain. it's a protective belief. others regress to living in total fear and helplessness - feeling as if their abuser has complete control over them and they'll never be free. this may last long after becoming physically safe. for others, an intense preoccupation with the relationship brews. everything revolves around where their perpetrator will be, what they'd think, if they could possibly run into each other, even trying to cross paths in some cases. some may isolate to extremes out of pure fear, even if the abuser is no longer local. there are so many possibilities and manifestations. in some instances, the preoccupation includes an obsession with revenge. now, that doesn't necessarily mean plotting or violence, but obsessing over how much their abuser deserves revenge and wishing it'd come -- sometimes to the point they can't just live their lives for themselves, not until they feel the world has made them pay in some way. (which, rarely happens.)
.
these are incredibly tricky, complicated situations and ones thattherapy, or an incredibly stable and trustworthy support network, is needed to remedy. it is possible to break free of these distortions - to see them as the perpetrator they really are, and you as the strong person you are. independently. strong. whole.
.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
today, iâ€™ve had a moment of clarity. where the silence drown out self doubt, distraction and rejection. 
a moment when your brain shuts up & you see the empowerment within you. unyielding, persisting grit throughout your journey. through abuse, betrayal, grief...& heart break. the mind is resilient, but the mind can also be the enemy. desires can be potent. passion can be unhinged. the edge is tempting. but choice is your weapon, if wielded correctly. choice sometimes feels impossible. you hear â€œchoose happinessâ€, â€œchoose joyâ€. if i could simply choose to change, we would all be okay, like choosing to eat, now iâ€™m not hungry. 
happiness & mental wellness isnt a ridged choice. itâ€™s not simply choosing, its embodying the choice. letting it flow through you.  truly believing in it.
if your choice is to be happyâ€”one reforming choice may not make you happy today, but small embodied, organic choices made for yourself, will change you & the invisible will become visible. 
our minds were not made to be happy. our minds were made to survive. happiness has to be exercised. invested into. and importantly, understood, on a personal, individual level. recognize your triggers, then avoid that shit! label what stresses & hurts you, then say â€œnoâ€ to it, unapologetically.
and my friends, recognize that some days you will not be happy, & that is okay! ride it out & if you find yourself there too long, own it & reach out. you are one of billions on this planet. and i promise you thousands of humans, will offer you affirmation, encouragement, resources, & love. in the states, our world is where mental health resources, churches, clubs, free activities that promote community interaction, self help books & blogs & positive social media pages are within our fingertips! if youâ€™re reading this, you already have the source in your hands to reach for change.
small, organic choices. 
one drop at a time. a steady drop will fill up your cup. you are not assigned to be a deteriorating human. donâ€™t believe it. everything begins in the mind.
choice is your weapon. 
redefine yourself. 
i believe in you. i believe in me. if it werenâ€™t for second chances, weâ€™d all be alone.

text:
on friday @cyclesandsex sent out a
new email newsletter. (itâ€™s fire, you should sign up, link in bio). like any good self-sabotager, i checked mailchimp for who unsubscribed.Â (donâ€™t do that.) some folks who unsubscribed checked â€œthese emails are #inappropriateâ€. i immediately felt #shame that the thing i'm working on is something that people deem inappropriate, improper, perverse, graceless.
i want to clarify:
i personally donâ€™t feel strongly about sex positivity, i feel strongly about social equity. (side-note) why do we even say "sex positive" as if anyone is "sex negativeâ€ the first place? the whole reason every one of us is here is because people had sex. i am the product of a sperm donor, and even he had sex (with himself) in order for sperm to come out and be put inside my mother.Â Â so, everyone is actuallyÂ â€œsex posâ€ because it's the only way the human species lives on.
what i feel strongly about is that you have #access to all the info about your body. this is social #equity. equity means starting from the same place, giving people what they need to be #successful. the fundamental way women and gender-non conforming people have experienced inequity (and oppression) starts with sex and reproductive health. information, access, research, institutions, opportunity, innovation, policy, religion, choice and societal norms have been built from an inequitable place around this topic. the #metoo movement is directly related to gender inequity around sex.
and so its time. govenment and institutions are not solving the problem (in fact they are contibuting to it.) from a business standpoint, there is a ravenous, uncharted market. which means mucho $$. #impactinvesting.
i am a part of building services and products that people need in order to find equity with their bodies and gender. the content will challenge social norms of what feels appropriate. because social norms are fucked up and disempower people, especially people of color and women. and i believe, if people have access to reliable information and support, they will be more free and empowered in their bodies and that will seep into all areas of their lives. 
sign up for my #newsletter. link in bio. âœŒğŸ¼

text:
first things first let me just say no one is or will ever be responsible for my thoughts and actions. a person's beliefs good or bad cannot determine how i choose to live my live, it merely creates clarity for me on the journey through life. i am sick to my back teeth of hearing about these sorry excuses of a black woman going on about how the black male and the beauty industry is the sole responsibility for their lack of esteem. ah ah! if you choose to give up the rights to be the master of your faith, how is that the fault of the black male let alone anyone but yourselves? one tree does not make a forest and the beauty of a forest is in its diversity, so why the hell do you dummies keep on about different individuals dwelling together regardless of colour or creed as the reference for your self-loathing and self-destruction? i.e (skin whitening) this sort of pass the buck kaka must cease at once! long before it was easy or fashionable to "blame the rain" for your woes, a group of strong  black women from the past for whom i learnt my game from and came from stood their grounds no matter the obstacles life throws up. (nanny of the maroon) these strenght of a woman was shown in their principles and beliefs that they would rather die for than to give in. so please go ahead and live the rest of your pathetic existence in silence with your woe me defeatism for i've got work to do protecting my daughters and strengthening them in the way some great black women did guiding me.

text:
i was initially so tired of trying to make guys see why believing survivors is so fkn important and also obvious. it made me so damn crazy that they couldn't understand something this basic. how could anyone be scared of being falsely accused if you've done nothing wrong? and instead of supporting us you literally choose to "not trust girls after this #metoo movement" ? seriously?
but then after a little thinking i was actually happy. yes, if you are scared, be even more scared. we've been scared of getting raped and molested everywhere we go since forever and now your time is up. you should be oh so scared because you're so not gonna be spared if you've even remotely wronged us.
-nida

text:
it's been a while... we get a lot of mixed signals sometimes and it's not always easy to separate the good ones from the bad ones because ... unfortunately... there is no handbook.

while it's hard to understand, we have to listen to what we know before we try to understand why it doesn't match what we feel most the time.

trust yourself, take the leap of faith and remember that behind every bad decision there's a lesson to be learned and behind every good decision, doors open that will take you far .mentally. physically. & emotionally. 
essentially, there's no wrong decision just figuring out which ones are the good ones vs the bad ones.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

a breakdown of
"i like beer ğŸº"
in 2018 america.

my message to justice k:

what we cannot have is a long law nobody understands. i like beer. justice k says. me too, i say. 
the me too movement is convinced that the question and that answer has everything to do with shared experience. it's a sensitive topic. 
me too could apply to liking beer. 
me too could apply to things like rape and sexual assault. 
being against the #metoo movement is a hard thing to do. but the form it has taken on lately is just letting things go too far in the feminist movement. i have to make a comment about the topic at this time. 
having deliberated with my thoughts on this issue for a long time, and in witnessing all things [pro-metoo] through the years, there is a sad reality to be addressed. this whole hashtag movement is about sharing the details and stories of those brave enough to use their voice and proclaim: yes, #metoo.

all supporters of the social movement are seeing a lot of stories and gaining their own courage to come forward and seek to be recognized as a way to heal. 
that's a good aspect of the hashtag. 
there is also a way more negative side of the hashtag and it's implications should the hashtag continue to be monopolized by victims of assault. 
can we get to the point where i can use a #metoo hashtag in the context of something like soup. 
ok here focus on this non complex example and enjoy the use case. someone has probably thought about this before. 
me @chrisincontext
"i'm having soup"

friend_npc2638:
"metoo"
#metoo

so let's advocate in favor of the #metoo hashtag becoming more balanced over time, and let's never slide to the point when we must argue very much about the merits of it's only fair and common use being in the context of rape.

text:
what is #himpathy
.
a pathological moral tendency to feel sorry exclusively for the alleged male perpetrator â€” it was too long ago; he was just a boy; it was a case of mistaken identity â€” while relentlessly casting suspicion upon the female accusers.
â€“  #katemanne
.
one need not look further than @realdonaldtrump to see this at play in multiple ways. we note the deference that he has been afforded when there has been irrefutable evidence of his misogynistic actions, views, and language that is unacceptable of anyone, let alone someone in the position he currently holds. this bad behaviour extends most recently to his response to #christineblaseyford and her testimony about her experience with #brettkavanagh. .
the response is not only asinine and completely negligent, but it speaks to everything that is wrong with the discourse of #violence in society, period. .
it is imperative to create space for women and girls to be safe, both to in their daily lives, but also in their expression of experience. there needs to be empathy, unconditional positive regard, and a sincere desire to understand their experience and not respond in any way other than to be supportive. understanding that making excuses for those that have played any role in perpetrating these experiences is harmful for any victim.
.
over the years, i have become more aware of my own #privilege as a white male and what it affords me, but it is certainly still something that i am working on understanding and applying appropriately to better understand the experiences of those around me. examples of my privilege: the ability to walk alone at night without feeling unsafe, the worry of sexual assault is completely off my radar, the fact that i enjoy the safety in nearly every single aspect of my life to show up however i choose with low risk to my health, safety, reputation or experience. privilege. i regularly challenge myself to check my own biases in how i show up to others in my life to support equity and be an ally. #allyisaverb
.
join me oct 30 @lululemonto at 96 ossington at 7pm with @nextgenmen to have a broader conversation about himpathy

text:
monday feels.

absolutely humbled to meet some incredible people this weekend who follow me for the reasons that matter to me, and it remind me exactly why im doing what i do.

i didn't set out doing this to try and be some superstar because that's not going to happen, nor is it what i care about in the slightest. im not trying to "get attention" unlike some people think either, my ultimate goal is just to remind people who they are, that they matter and they can do anything.

so go get it fam! monday's as good a day as any!

text:
cristiano ronaldo, the most famous and well known athlete on the planet, has been accused of rape. kathryn mayorga, an american from nevada, is claiming he raped her in a las vegas hotel in 2009. she then alleges that he coerced her into keeping quiet for $375,000. ronaldoâ€™s lawyer, has conceded the existence of the settlement, but has also said it is â€œby no means an admission of guilt,â€. this story has yet to reach a conclusions, yet ramifications have already been felt. while we donâ€™t know if ronaldo is innocent or not, this allegation has already irreparably damaged his reputation. if for a second we extrapolate a scenario where he is innocent, then itâ€™s not fair that his public image has been deteriorated over false claims. ronaldo despite his oftentimes unappealing demeanor on the pitch, is a very active philanthropist, and seems to always do good at every opportunity he gets. so if heâ€™s innocent, then this is a very ugly, unfortunate thing to happen. as a public figure, your name and reputation is a very valuable/important thing, as it effects how you live and how youâ€™re treated by people, and even how your family will be treated. that said, he could very well be guilty. and if he is, he deserves far worse than the aforementioned. cases such as these are always difficult to gauge, as you want to follow the â€œinnocent until proven guilty,â€ mantra, but oftentimes, people take up positions and judge prior to the case being resolved. kathryn mayorga for her part, said she was inspired from the #metoo movement to bring the allegations up again. while i have no personal opinion on this particular case at this point, i do believe that in the long run, this current time period of women speaking out will result in a better society, as it will deter men considering assault and make them more aware of their actions and how they effect others.
(source: independent sport)

jessy niteâ€™s collaboration with paloma teppa of plant the future takes a poetic phrase by the artist and translates it into a plant-based biophiliac work. paloma teppa is an artist who founded plant the futureâ€”a nature-inspired design firm based in miami. she embraces biophilia by fusing art and nature and in this case, has created an installation that will grow and flourish and ultimately decay during the course of its exhibition.
â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €â €
last december during miami art week, @anthony_spinello and @zoelukov curated the first in a series of alternative art fairs, entitled â€œfair.â€ fair., an alternative non-commercial art fair that took place december 7-10, 2017 at brickell city centre, served as a platform for a diverse and multigenerational group of women artists. fair. seeked to address gender inequality in the art world and beyond by providing space for radical women artists to create site-specific interventions in a non-traditional venue.

text_retweet:
#reigninpower ğŸ‘‘ #ntozakeshange posted @withrepost â€¢ @buffaloseminarytheatre new yorkÂ â€“ playwright, poet and author ntozake shange, whose most acclaimed theater piece is the 1975 tony award-nominated play "for colored girls who have considered suicide/when the rainbow is enuf," died saturday, according to her daughter. she was 70.

shange's "for colored girls" describes the racism, sexism, violence and rape experienced by seven black women. it has been influential to generations of progressive thinkers, fromÂ #metoo architect tarana burkeÂ to pulitzer prize-winning playwright lynn nottage. after learning of shange's death, nottage called her "our warrior poet/dramatist." "she spoke for, and in fact embodied, the ongoing struggle of black women and girls to live with dignity and respect in the context of systemic racism, sexism and oppression," the author's daughter said. "for colored girls" is an interwoven series of poetic monologues set to music â€“ shange coined the form a "choreopoem" for it â€“ by african-american women, each identified only by a color that she wears.

it played some 750 performances on broadway â€“ only the second play by an african-american woman after "a raisin in the sun" â€“ and was turned into a feature film byÂ tyler perryÂ starring thandie newton, anika noni rose, kerry washington andÂ janet jackson.

born paulette williams in trenton, new jersey, she went on to graduate from barnard college and got a master's degree from the university of southern california.  she later assumed a new zulu name: ntozake means "she who comes with her own things" and shange means "she who walks like a lion." she worked with such black theater companies as the lorraine hansberry theatre in san francisco; the new freedom theater in philadelphia; crossroads theatre company in new brunswick, new jersey; st. louis black rep; penumbra theatre in st. paul, minnesota; and the ensemble theatre in houston, texas.

shange taught at brown university, rice university, villanova university, depaul university, prairie view university and sonoma state univ. she also lectured at yale, howard, new york university, among others.
-usa today

text:
earlier today i watched 'feminists: what were they thinking?' on netflix and it was just what i needed

this documentary speaks to dozens of women about their experiences and asks them what it is that makes them so passionate about fighting for gender equality

speaking up about inequality can be hard in a world that constantly tells you to be quiet and people-pleasing and inoffensive. and i don't know about you, but i often look at powerful and successful women and assume they've got their shit together and couldn't possibly experience the self doubt, self censorship and self deprecating worries that i often do, but each interview is so heartwarming, inspiring and relatable that it left me thinking "i'm doing just fine and i'm doing what's right" ğŸ’ª 
it's a really good watch and i hope it'll make you feel as brave, unapologetic and powerful as it's made me feel

text:
there are two things the human body and caviar have in common: water and protein. the skin and caviar are mostly made up of water and protein. because of this similarity in the cellular structure, all the nutrients from the caviar extract can be easily absorbed by our skin.

water and protein play an essential role in attaining a youthful and hydrated skin. it can also slow down the maturing of skin by replenishing skin tissues and improving skin elasticity.10

protein is also a big factor in keeping skin free from wrinkles, fine lines, and sagging. every single cell in the body needs protein to repair and construct new cell tissues.12 amino acids are the building blocks of protein and these amino acids also help in improving the skinâ€™s texture and tone.

text:
#ripntozakeshange 
playwright, poet and author ntozake shange, whose most acclaimed theater piece is the 1975 tony award-nominated play "for colored girls who have considered suicide/when the rainbow is enuf," died saturday, according to her daughter. she was 70.

shange's "for colored girls" describes the racism, sexism, violence and rape experienced by seven black women. it has been influential to generations of progressive thinkers, from #metoo architect tarana burke to pulitzer prize-winning playwright lynn nottage. after learning of shange's death, nottage called her "our warrior poet/dramatist."

text: iâ€™m not happy with these leaves. iâ€™ve been experimenting with different media to get more transparency out of these pieces, and while the parchment paper gave me what i needed as far as light goes, the ink bled into the paper and pigment. at first i was frustrated and ready to throw the leaves away, but then it got me thinking about how we typically only share the flawless with one another- especially on social media. itâ€™s so easy to curate an idyllic brand on instagram and force the world to see you as perfect. as someone who never makes mistakes and gets it right the first time and every time. in the past, iâ€™ve found that trying to do that is very bad for my anxiety. even the smallest of errors is amplified by the negative little voices in my head when iâ€™ve striven for perfection and missed the mark. it causes me to compare myself to other creators, and comparison is a thief of joy, ultimately. so iâ€™m not going to do that. iâ€™m going to share the mistakes. iâ€™m going to embrace the errors. iâ€™m going to celebrate my flaws and the flaws i create. these leaves may not have turned out the way i wanted, but iâ€™ll repurpose them. into what, iâ€™m not sure at the moment. but iâ€™ll figure it out as i go. and iâ€™m going to do my best to apply that notion to my survivorship. the slips and falls caused by my anxiety and cptsd may not be beautiful, but they are meaningful. i may not understand them right away, but their significance will be revealed in time. âœ¨#cptsd #anxiety #mentalhealth #selfcare #survivorselfcare #survivor #believesurvivors #metoo #artist #wip #flawsandall

text:
what might it be like to sit in a space of not being okay? .
.
.
i sat in my car a few weeks back noticing that i wasnâ€™t okay. i was experiencing a whole range of emotions and feelings. and as i sat i noticed myself go into a place i call â€œtherapy fix it mode.â€ what skills could i employ to help myself feel better? and while skills can be incredibly useful, they are not there to help us fix ourselves, they are there to help us understand and support ourselves. it was in that moment that i said out loud to myself, â€˜iâ€™m not okay and i donâ€™t need to do anything about it.â€™ then writing down in my phone:
.
.
there is incredible vulnerability, healing and power in acknowledging that you arenâ€™t okay and not trying to fix it. .
.
ah-ha moments still come, because the work still comes.
.
.
if an almost 20 year yoga practice has taught me anything it has taught me that sitting in discomfort will eventually soften. because here is the thingâ€”there is nothing wrong with not feeling okay, with feeling meh, sad, or uncertain. there is nothing wrong with your emotions and feelings, just like there is nothing wrong with mine. they arenâ€™t good or bad, they in both complexity and simplicity...are. and while i am a trained mental health professional, iâ€™m going to let you in on somethingâ€”iâ€™m a human first who is still doing her work. .
.
i often tell my clients to go underneath a feeling or an emotion and to sit there. just sit. it can be difficultâ€”iâ€™m often asked: â€œwhat do i do from there?â€ you sit and notice, i answer. we live in a culture that suggests fixing something is what will make it better. fixing is another way that we stuff our emotions and feelings down invalidating what we are experiencing. itâ€™s like a game of whack-a-mole, we stuff or try to fix and then something pops up in another part of our life. so what if we mindfully watch what is happening? without the need to fix. without shame. rather, a f*ck-ton of compassion, and trust in ourselves that it is actually okay to let ourselves be something other than happy.
.
.
.
[photo caption reads: there is incredible vulnerability, healing and power in acknowledging that you arenâ€™t okay and not trying to fix it. ]
name: elisabeth t. lilja/MSW/CSW/RYT

text:
take the time to observe and learn from what is around us. this fog reminds me of my past. it's hovering over this strong beautiful mountain but then the wind blows the fog away so the sun can shine on the mountain once again, allowing life to blossom. mother nature teaching us about teamwork and love.
i am so very blessed to have people that blow away the darkness of my past when i am unable to do so and those that cover me in warmth and love giving me strength to keep moving forward in my journey of healing. 
it is not just my passion it is my responsibility to pass this love on to others.

text:
today i got a wake up call,
i was shocked still but ignored it all,
i opened the door and walked away,
while like me others they slay,
i ran with all i had,
i stopped to take a breathe i was sad,
i was angry,
with all tom, dicks & harry,
i cried my lungs out
touched a few decibels 
no humans though
there has to be a way to take out this anger,
this frustration,
this feeling sorry,
this going mad,
stop
so here is to victims of power
victims of comments that shower,
india will rise again,
to the ones who should be shamed,
to whose manipulations we are aimed,
i will not loose again,
to the couches & fame,
unbottle the bottled feelings,
i am for me too 
are you?

the series of sexual assault , which all took place in los angeles county ,involve aspiring models whom walker contacted under the premise of being hired for professional work . however, once they were alone , each victim reported that walker
assaulted  them , police say 
walker 's charges include five counts of  forcible rape , three counts of sexual penetration by a foreign object , and one count of forcible oral copulation, according to court documents obtained by the los angeles times 
walker is being held on $1,080,000 bail 
and his next court date is scheduled for

text:
#davidchappelle - when the boys club mentality wins over an otherwise impressive sense for justice!

iâ€™ve taken my sunday coffee time to write my part on the â€˜louis ckâ€™ debacle, because when i went to see chappelleâ€™s show in berlin on friday night, i got to see my all-time comedy hero at his most imprudent on this topic, which made it clear to me that itâ€™s still important to speak out in support of the affected women, #danamingoodman , #juliawolov , abby schachner, rebecca corey etc. 
when asked about louis ckâ€™s return to the stage, hereâ€™s what chappelle -quote - â€˜not only thinks, but knowsâ€™: â€œhe didnâ€™t harm anyone, he didnâ€™t lock the door, so a talent like that should not be expelled from the stage any longerâ€™.â€ well chappelle, hereâ€™s where your arguments are flawed and unrighteously spurred a whole crowd to dismiss a very important and serious matter: 
failed argument numero uno: â€œhe didnâ€™t harm themâ€ - â€¦. you sure, pal? mental harm, caused by a demeaning act and the accompanying fear, not a thing? is it really hard to imagine these women fearing harm to their careers by this industry dominating individual (remember, they too are comedians)? also recalling the textbook abuse case for women - â€œif you canâ€™t show a bruise, nothing can be done just yetâ€ - thanks chappelle, youâ€™re following in great footsteps there!

failed argument numero dos: â€œhe didnâ€™t lock the doorâ€ - ...ahh, so there was no physical barrier preventing women from leaving? cool, yea..except, what about that huge chubby dude in full-on agitated maturbation mode right in front of them? there is nothing more relatable than a woman calculating the risk of staying in this abusive situation vs. getting up and risking a potentially more aggressive and physical reaction by c.k.. come on dude, howâ€™d you miss that?

i believe you only miss that if being part of the comedy â€˜boys clubâ€™ and backing your buddy takes priority over emphasizing with these women - aka your other colleagues! disappointing statement by an otherwise outstandingly aware artist and defender of womenâ€™s rights... #boysclubclosing #withwomen  #davidchappelle #timesup #metoo
name: Jenny Christina Conrads

jessy niteâ€™s collaboration with paloma teppa of plant the future takes a poetic phrase by the artist and translates it into a plant-based biophiliac work. paloma teppa is an artist who founded plant the futureâ€”a nature-inspired design firm based in miami. she embraces biophilia by fusing art and nature and in this case has created an installation that will grow and flourish and ultimately decay during the course of its exhibition.

text:
everyone knows #donaldtrump has a complicated relationship with the truth. but he flat out lied saturday evening to justify moving forward with a #campaignrally mere hours after 11 people were shot to death in a #pittsburgh synagogue. trump said that the #newyorkstockexchange reopened the day after the sept. 11, 2001 terrorist attacks, when in realityÂ it took several days for the markets to reopen.
.
â€œwith what happened early today, that horrible, horrible attack in pittsburgh, i was saying maybe i should cancel both this and that. and then i said to myself, i remembered dick russell, a friend of mine, great guy, he headed up the new york stock exchange on september 11th, and the new york stock exchange was open the following day,â€Â trump said during a campaign rally in illinois. â€œhe saidâ€”and what they had to do to open it you wouldnâ€™t believe, we wonâ€™t even talk to you about it. but he got that exchange open. we canâ€™t make these sick, demented, evil people important.â€.
.
that statement didnâ€™t come out of the blue. he had repeated aÂ less detailed distorted version of historyÂ earlier in the day during his remarks at the future farmers of america conference in indianapolis. â€œi remember when we had the attack in manhattan, we opened the stock exchange the next day,â€ trump said. â€œpeople were shocked.â€.
.
trumpâ€™s version of history sounds pretty incredible. but it just isnâ€™t true. both the new york stock exchange and nasdaq were closed until monday, sept. 17, which marked the longest closing of the markets since 1933.
 the u.s. exchanges were hardly alone as other markets around the world were closed as well. â€œitâ€™s easy to figure this outÂ using google,â€ notes the washington postâ€™s glenn kessler. â€œthereâ€™s even aÂ whole wikipedia page.â€.
.
it isnâ€™t just dates that trump got wrong in his little tale, but also names. while the president referenced â€œdick russell, a friend of mine,â€ the head of the nyse at the time was actually named dick grasso. #dickrussell was a senator from georgia who defended segregation.
.

text:
"she changes everything she touches and everything she touches changes. we are changers, everything we touch can change." these are the the words and an image from a performance at opus this year that struck me and stuck with me more than anything else i saw that night. it spoke to how i've been feeling lately about my calling and the people i want to surround myself with. it spoke to what's happening now.

the past week has been brutal. state-sponsored transphobia. calling refugees who are fleeing violence in their own countries terrorists, while the real terrorists are white men in our own country. racist, terrorist white men killing black and jewish people. attempted assassinations of democratic leaders by another racist, terrorist white man. all egged on by our fucking president (a racist, terrorist white man). voting is next week, and i've felt intensely anxious about it the closer we get. i'm sick and tired of people's excuses for not voting. i'm done with people who aren't willing to lift a finger or get outside their comfort zones to help our country.

everything we touch can change, yes. but everything hateful people touch can change, too. their attacks are changing our country in insidious ways and the only way to fight back is to touch more, affect more, than they do. *vote for candidates who care more about people + equality than tax cuts
*talk to your friends and family about voting
*volunteer for a phone bank, or for canvassing
*share resources and posts on social media to spread the word about the things that are affecting you and your loved ones
*call out every single iota of racism, misogyny, transphobia, and homophobia that you see and hear, everywhere you go

we won't let them stop us now. we are changers. comment below if you believe we can change this country... and inspire others by sharing what you're doing to help!

text:
the second sex is a 1949 book by the french existentialist simone de beauvoir, in which the author discusses the treatment of women throughout history. the second sex is a call to arms. it explains that women are often complicit in their own subordinated status. they consent to live as dolls, rather than full human beings. they accept the rewards of submissiveness: love, protection, approval. in this way, they are â€œpassive, lost, ruined.â€ de beauvoir demands that women sacrifice all this cosy bondage and fight to the death for a freedom which is both harrowing and thrilling. 
the book terrified me. it suggested that there was nowhere to hide, there was no excuse. published in 1949, it combines existential philosophy with a staggeringly broad analysis of womenâ€™s condition: from fashion to sex to mysticism. de beauvoir lampoons the myths that keep women in a passive position, such as the fairy-tale of romantic love, which promises salvation by a man. she warns of â€œthe harsh punishment inflicted upon the woman who has not taken her destiny into her own hands. ğŸ“¸ tag a fellow feminist who should see this! ğŸ“¸

text:
this is coming straight from our founder and our lead volunteer @thehealedwomanfoundation ,if you are in lagos and ogun state pls let's support this project and let's curb rape and child sexual abuse. my heart bleeds and my eyes are always filled with tears anytime i hear or see the any case of rape or child abuse, not just because i'm a survivor too but because it's getting too rampant and i will do my part to eradicate it. thanks to @faithakano for giving me the privilege. .

@regran_ed from @faithakano -
.
.
with our project, rescue the girl child, we will be visiting primary and secondary schools all over nigeria to educate female students about sexual abuse, child trafficking and other forms of abuse that can affect them. with this, we want to get to meet girls who are victims and offer them help in the form of counseling and by partnering with other organizations, get them legal help too.
.
.
our first tour will be next month, november 2018. our target is 20 schools within lagos and ogun states.
.
.
rescue the girl child tour needs partnership (most important), volunteering and donations to take it further. our target is to reach out to girls in all schools in nigeria.
.
.
to partner with us, volunteer, or make a donation, send an email to admin@thehealedwoman.org or call +2347069403717
.
.
cac/it/no 118484

text:
i have had friends reach out to me over the past few weeks to tell me they were thinking of me. it's unfortunate that the experiences of sexual assault survivors have become politicized. our stories are not supposed to be your weapons of partisan politics. i'm not a republican. i'm not a democrat. i'm not even a capital l libertarian. government is not your savior. you can go out and vote but sin will still be in the hearts of selfish and gross men and women. trump is not the christ nor is he the antichrist. politics as usual. political figures are not your friends. this is not a spectator sport. 
thank you to all my male friends who showed me immense respect, who prayed for me, walked me to and from class, male and female friends who walked with me and literally provided a physical barrier between my attacker and me, knew how difficult it was during chapel when the person played a part and stared down from the bleachers, lied and manipulated the police and the psychologist we were both assigned to, etc. thank you to my professors who accommodated my requests to not be in class with him. i want my friends to know it was not your fault. you are good friends. you and i did "everything right" to prevent what we could. the fault lies with one person alone and he will face judgment. god bless you.
#stopkavanaugh #confirmkavanaugh #libertarian #independentvoter #nevertrump #metoo #churchtoo #believeher #believewomen #timesup

text:
lemonade 
story by anonymous
.
.
.
lemonade
i got married 12 years back and had two children during this time. at first, i was quite happy but then things started to change or maybe everything was already like this and i was just too blind and didn't see anything. 
in my marriage, i have gone through physical violence and mental torture but i held myself back, for my children. i knew that they will never have comfortable standard of living if i decided to leave. 
there is only so much a human can take. on one fine day, after so many years, my shell broke down and i came outside with my children. it's been 4 months now and i still don't know where i have to go. we are still married, he didn't file a divorce instead he contacted my relatives to justify that it was all my fault and kept my documents.

there are nights on which i cry and wonder if it was my fault? if i hadn't raised my voice then maybe that slap would never came or if i had accepted the arrangements then at least my children would never had to witness their mother lying in floor with bruises on her face. and then there are some nights on which i just spend the whole time watching the ceiling. 
even after being so educated i can't help but think that maybe it is my fault. maybe my upbringing is at fault as we are taught to be submissive and blame ourselves for going against the grain. 
there is long way for me to go. i don't know what future holds for me. i don't know what i am going to do to survive or if i will ever recover. when life gives you lemons, you have to make lemonade. you don't get a choice because those lemons if lied around for too long, they are just going rot and add garbage to your life.

i have learnt this from the things that i have suffered.  but i have hope. i have decided to cling to it, for sake of bright future for my children.

art source - @weheartit
compiled by - @himangivarshney

text: a little over year ago i posted on here about self-care. i put off a mammogram that was so long overdue itâ€™s crazy when i think about it! i thank god for my friend melissa @cancerfashionista  @melissaberrypr  who is a brave beautiful survivor of breast cancer. once i heard her share her story, how could i not go? how could i not make a simple appointment and take an hour out of my day for something that could change my life so dramatically.  life is a gift every day and by not going i was slapping life in the face. and i have a son!  what was i thinking?! when i finally went last year i had a big scare, but thankfully everything turned out fine. because of the situation i was told that i need to go more regularly and again my crazy life took over this past year but this time i acknowledged that thereâ€™s only one me and i am the only one who can take care of me. no one will get me in for the mammogram unless i do it myself!  seeing all the amazing work that melissa has done for cancer survivors encourages me to make sure that i take care of myself. last week, as soon as i got home from a trip from az, i went in for my mammogram. afterwards, i was told to stay, as they needed to do more tests. again, like last time, there is now another scare and i will need to have a biopsy this week. honestly, i am extremely worried that they found something, but iâ€™m also extremely grateful that i went in.  i am remaining positive. and most importantly, iâ€™m proud i cared enough about myself and i believe â€œi got thisâ€! and trust me itâ€™s taken me many years to get to the point to have the confidence to make this statement. through a lot of work, survival, support of mentors and friends, iâ€™m here today to say i got whatever life brings to me!  and if i can encourage anyone who is reading this today to go and make that appointment that youâ€™ve been putting off, get that check up youâ€™ve been needing and to take care yourself then iâ€™m so glad i shared my story â¤ï¸

text:
an exclusive interview of sohaila abdulaziz for @bazaarindia .. dear all,
iâ€™m thrilled to announce that my book, what we talk about when we talk about rape, is about to make its way into bookstores all over the world. it will be available in asia (october 25), europe (october 25), australia/new zealand (october 29) and north america (november 27). you can also find it as an e-book or an audiobook (read by me). i started writing this book with the premise that i was going to write about an obscure subject. well! as soon as i wrote the introduction about how nobody talks about rape, #metoo burst upon the american scene. as the book comes out, #metooindia is so enthralling that i can no longer swear off twitter.  while the book is being published when the topic is hot, it is not intended to be a book just for this moment. it is based on my thinking about rape over more than three decades. in the introduction, i write:

rape drains the light. like j.k. rowlingâ€™s fantastically terrifying dementors, it sucks joy. and, along with draining the light from victimsâ€™ lives, it tends to drain the light from sensible conversation. discussions about rape are so often irrational, and sometimes outright bizarre. itâ€™s the only crime to which people respond by wanting to lock up the victims. itâ€™s the only crime that is so bad that victims are supposed to be destroyed beyond repair by it, but simultaneously not so bad that the men who do it should be treated like other criminals.  i want to let some light back in.

to do that, i talked with people all over the world, read, thought, and sat at my window and wrote. itâ€™s been a fascinating experience. the next year promises to be as fascinating, as i travel the world with the book, from jaipur to sydney.

early reviews have been promising, and iâ€™ve been gratified by all the fantastic endorsements from people i truly admire, and the interviews and social media shout-outs.

i will never ask you if you read my book. thatâ€™s just rude. but if you do want to, you can get it in all the usual ways: your local bookstore, your trusty pre-order button, the library. 
http://www.sohailaink.com/
https://twitter.com/sohailaabdulali

text:
the struggle is real!

it's sad to realize that the only thing i get to read everyday whether it's a local newspaper or an online blog revolves only around the negative side of the #metoo campaign. instead of appreciating that women are coming out to tell their horrifying stories, the crowd is proving a point that silence is really golden. kudos to the women who've gathered the courage to come out and speak up, and i'm so sorry for the negative response that so many of you are getting. i feel ashamed to live in a society where people are always ready to pick up a fight and pass nonsensical judgements about topics and stories where they weren't even present; the same people are also ever ready to pose as feminists on their social media handles. great job done hypocrite society! you make us think twice before speaking the truth.

text:
rest well, sister.

mediascope - ntozake shange, writer ofÂ for colored girls, has passed away

playwright, poet and author ntozake shange, whose most acclaimed theater piece is the 1975 tony award-nominated play "for colored girls who have considered suicide/when the rainbow is enuf," died saturday, according to her daughter. she was 70.

shange's "for colored girls" describes the racism, sexism, violence and rape experienced by seven black women. it has been influential to generations of progressive thinkers, from #metoo architect tarana burke to pulitzer prize-winning playwright lynn nottage. after learning of shange's death, nottage called her "our warrior poet/dramatist." savannah shange, a professor of anthropology at the university of california at santa cruz, said saturday that her mother died in her sleep at an assisted living facility in bowie, maryland. she had suffered a series of strokes in 2004. "she spoke for, and in fact embodied, the ongoing struggle of black women and girls to live with dignity and respect in the context of systemic racism, sexism and oppression," savannah shange said.

read more at https://bit.ly/2d8yesh

text:
playwright, poet and author ntozake shange, whose most acclaimed theater piece is the 1975 tony award-nominated play "for colored girls who have considered suicide/when the rainbow is enuf," died saturday, according to her daughter. she was 70.
shange's "for colored girls" describes the racism, sexism, violence and rape experienced by seven black women. it has been influential to generations of progressive thinkers, from #metoo architect tarana burke to pulitzer prize-winning playwright lynn nottage. after learning of shange's death, nottage called her "our warrior poet/dramatist." savannah shange, a professor of anthropology at the university of california at santa cruz, said saturday that her mother died in her sleep at an assisted living facility in bowie, maryland. she had suffered a series of strokes in 2004. "she spoke for, and in fact embodied, the ongoing struggle of black women and girls to live with dignity and respect in the context of systemic racism, sexism and oppression," savannah shange said. "for colored girls" is an interwoven series of poetic monologues set to music â€” shange coined the form a "choreopoem" for it â€” by african-american women, each identified only by a color that she wears.

shange used idiosyncratic punctuation and nonstandard spellings in her work, challenging conventions. one of her characters shouts, "i will raise my voice / & scream & holler / & break things & race the engine / & tell all yr secrets bout yrself to yr face."
it played some 750 performances on broadway â€” only the second play by an african-american woman after "a raisin in the sun" â€” and was turned into a feature film by tyler perry starring thandie newton, anika noni rose, kerry washington and janet jackson.

text:
don't look at her that way, my heart and my mind say,
is it her beauty that drives me towards her, or is it my carnal urge making her diginity a blur? 
oh my perverted mind, is it love or lust in my heart, finally not wanting to hide?
the angel sitting on my right shoulder says, "don't take pride by taking away her pride." the devil murmurs in my left ear, "show her your brutal side. let the vulture in you be satisfied."
her innocence is not for you to take away, the sun is shining but it is not the time to make hay.

being a man is an ability you can use to its full capacity because, a lone woman is not an opportunity but a responsibility.

lots of blove! ğŸ’™

text:
morning flows. a lot of travel, long plane and car rides, and also some stress (for those of you have have been reading on my involvement in the #metoo movement) had made my body so stiff. itâ€™s amazing how the body reacts to all these factors. this morning i gave my body some much needed nourishment. i focussed on a long, slow and easy practice with deep deep breathes and stretches. i have sped up the video three times so you can imagine how slow i was going. here are some of the standing poses i did. remember, when you balance your body physically, you are working on mental, and emotional balance as well. 
#yogaeverydamnday #irayoga

text:
silence is an answer. 
no response is a response. .
.
recently, i had to make a decision.
.
.
i had to decide between my comfort or my conviction.  i had to look at myself in the mirror and say, "do you really stand with @repmaxinewaters who has been called "low iq" (just because 45 can get away with insinuating that black women are stupid)? do you really have her back??
.
.
i had to say, "kelly are you truly disgusted that 500 young brown kids may never see their parents again after peacefully seeking asylum in the us?"
.
.
"kelly, did 45's attack on #christinablaseyford who courageously spoke up for you and others who are victims of #sexualassault really disturb you?" are you sincerely grateful to her?
.
.
"...and kelly what about everything else you have said over the past two years?  when the wind blows your direction, what will you do?"
.
.
i took a stand.  and i learned who stands with me... who cheers me on in public.  who cheers me on in private spaces.  i learned who has concern for my safety.
.
.
it wasn't comfortable.  but that may be the point of it all.  do we only take a stand when it's safe?  when there is no personal sacrifice??? think about it.
.
.
yeah, it would be great if we could all pretend like what is happening isn't happening.  because it may not have happened to you.  but, to the people in the back row:  its happening. .
.
at first it was lonely... i almost second-guessed my decision.  but i chose to remain on the road less traveled.  and guess what:  during that solo trip, i bumped into angels at every turn!! ğŸ™ŒğŸ½
.
.
shout out to the #metoo founders.  to the #parklandshooting organizers of #marchforourlives. to the creators of #blacklivesmatter.  to the #womensmarch leadership. to the #nodapl champions.  you learned it isn't easy, but you are not alone.

if you are afraid to take a stand, know this:  you are not alone. ğŸ’¯#truestory

text:
.
hollow hearts and hungry souls 
little girl walking home
she creeps softly among the shadows, hiding herself under the cover of darkness
yet you seek her out, tracing out her silhouette within the murky gloom
conjuring a foreboding mixture of apprehension and distress that burns within her veins 
she tries to ignore the thundering of her heart as your eyes rake over the framework of her flesh
but anxiety runs bone deep, settling into the blood in her marrow 
and restlessness is like a second skin, close-fitted and constricting, too tight too small and slowly pulling at the seams
prickling with sensation as she squirms uncomfortably beneath the heat of your gaze
.
.
.
.
.
